  {
    "search_query": "key risk categories for NHS healthcare investment projects",
    "search_results": {
      "organic": [
        {
          "title": "NHS capital investment: five key considerations for getting it right",
          "link": "https://www.health.org.uk/news-and-comment/blogs/nhs-capital-investment-key-considerations-for-getting-it-right",
          "snippet": "How can decision makers without analytical training arrive at a first, and rough, judgement about...\n\nReceive the latest news and updates\n\nfrom the Health Foundation\n\nCopyright The Health Foundation 2025. Registered charity number 286967.\n\n# NHS capital investment: five key considerations for getting it right\n\n## Insights and analysis\n\n## 1\\. Assess where capital need is greatest\n\n## 2\\. Organise capital infrastructure to best deliver value for money\n\n## 3\\. Ensure support for NHS staff accompanies capital investment\n\n## 4\\. Consider investing in other models of care that might be more effective\n\n## 5\\. Ensure resources are distributed to support local populations and wider local economies\n\n## Further reading\n\n## You might also like...\n\n### Labour’s first 100 days in health and care policy\n\n### Labour's commitment to new hospital programme is welcome but sustained investment still needed\n",
          "date": "Oct 17, 2024",
          "position": 1
        },
        {
          "title": "Risk management in the NHS: governance, finance and clinical risk",
          "link": "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4953411/",
          "snippet": "A risk management programme was introduced by the NHS Litigation Authority (NHSLA) in 1995, although it was 2000 before it was fully implemented. The core of this programme is provided by a range of NHSLA standards and assessments, and it is a requirement of continued membership of the Clinical Negligence Scheme for Trusts (CNST) that hospitals are subject to audit by the NHSLA. A set of risk management standards for each type of healthcare organisation was developed incorporating organisational, clinical, and health and safety risks ( www.nhsla.com).\n\nAll the NHSLA standards are divided into three ‘levels’. NHS organisations which achieve success at level one in the relevant standards receive a 10% discount on their CNST contributions, with discounts of 20% and 30% available to those passing to levels two and three respectively. Members of the CNST scheme are required to achieve level one compliance and are assessed on an annual basis until this is achieved.",
          "position": 2
        },
        {
          "title": "[PDF] An exemplar operational risk management strategy | NHS England",
          "link": "https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/An_exemplar_operational_risk_management_strategy.pdf",
          "snippet": "2 The initial stage of the process is aimed at addressing the question “What are the current and future risks?” It comprises a comprehensive analysis of the current risk position and performance of the trust in relation to the services it provides and the human resources and physical assets that it utilises. The key objective of this stage is to set a baseline for the development of risk reduction options.\n\n3.3 One of the key factors in the strategic management of operational risks is their categorisation. Risk categories should be – amongst other things – specific, significant, consistent, measurable and comprehensive. Categories may be defined in any number of ways including by target, hazard, consequence, activity, department, safeguards and/or legislation etc.\n\n3.4 The second stage of the process is concerned with addressing the question “What do we want our levels of risk to be?",
          "position": 3
        },
        {
          "title": "[PDF] Managing Risk in the NHS - PwC",
          "link": "https://www.pwc.co.uk/healthcare/pdf/managing-risk-in-nhs-2023.pdf",
          "snippet": "At an individual risk level, we identified all those risks that were similar in nature, and gave them all a generic risk title, allowing us to identify those risks common to a number of risk registers, for example financial performance, workforce, etc.\n\nThe average residual scores for impact and likelihood were calculated along with the proportion of the population citing each risk. This then allowed us to rank the risks in order of magnitude based upon those values.\n\nWe identified the type of risk as one of 10 broad categories as set out in Appendix A: patient care, financial performance, workforce, IT infrastructure, partnerships, COVID-19, estates infrastructure, regulatory actions, sustainable services, and strategic objectives.\n\nThe detailed findings of our analysis are set out in the remainder of this document.\n\nAlthough the peak of COVID-19 has passed the NHS continues to tackle the impact of the pandemic and our analysis shows this is still resulting in a number of significant risks for the sector.",
          "position": 4
        },
        {
          "title": "Principles for assessing and managing risks across integrated care ...",
          "link": "https://www.england.nhs.uk/long-read/principles-for-assessing-and-managing-risks-across-integrated-care-systems/",
          "snippet": "The NQB would like to specifically thank the NHS England South West Clinical Quality Team for its work in developing these principles.\n\nThis document complements the National Quality Board’s (NQB) other guidance for integrated care systems (ICSs), and particularly the National Risk Response and Escalation Guidance which sets out how quality risks and concerns should be managed in ICSs.  The document sets out key principles to use when assessing risks in environments or scenarios that are rapidly changing or based on multiple factors (e.g. multiple services/organisations involved). Whether it is unprecedented levels of pressure, unit and care home closures, new technologies, IT systems or medicines coming onto the market, pandemics or public health emergencies, health and care organisations are faced with increasing complexity.\n\nIndividual health and care organisations, including providers, Integrated Care Boards (ICBs) and Local Authorities, must ensure their approach to risk management meets recognised standards and best practice (key guidance on risk assessment in health and care includes the National Patient Safety Agency’s Risk Matrix for Risk Managers, 2008), including: agreed risk appetite statements;",
          "date": "Dec 4, 2024",
          "attributes": {
            "Missing": "investment | Show results with:investment"
          },
          "sitelinks": [
            {
              "title": "Principles For Assessing And...",
              "link": "https://www.england.nhs.uk/long-read/principles-for-assessing-and-managing-risks-across-integrated-care-systems/#:~:text=Principles%20for%20assessing%20and%20managing%20risks%20across%20integrated%20care%20systems,-National%20Quality%20Board"
            },
            {
              "title": "Key Principles For Assessing...",
              "link": "https://www.england.nhs.uk/long-read/principles-for-assessing-and-managing-risks-across-integrated-care-systems/#:~:text=Key%20principles%20for%20assessing%20risks%20across%20integrated%20care%20systems,-The%20table%20below%20sets%20out"
            },
            {
              "title": "Annex A: Case Studies",
              "link": "https://www.england.nhs.uk/long-read/principles-for-assessing-and-managing-risks-across-integrated-care-systems/#:~:text=Annex%20A%3A%20Case%20studies,-Case%20study%201%20%2D%2D%20closure"
            }
          ],
          "position": 5
        }
      ]
    }
