  {
    "search_query": "specific regulatory risks NHS medical innovation funding",
    "search_results": {
      "organic": [
        {
          "title": "Opportunities and Risks of UK Medical Device Reform - PMC",
          "link": "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9007047/",
          "snippet": "32 key stakeholders across the medical device sector were identified both from the public and private sectors.\n\nOpportunities relating to regulatory independence were identified, including the potential to create and implement a regulatory framework that ensures availability of medical devices; innovation and investment potential; and safety to the citizens of the UK. The most significant risks identified included threats to the safety of individual patients and the wider health system arising from the delay in awaiting regulatory approval due to the shortage of approved bodies; and reduced competitiveness of UK market and device manufacturers. Recommendations were identified to mitigate risks, centred on harnessing broader cross-sector collaborations, promoting patient and public partnership, and maximizing international engagement.\n\n",
          "position": 1
        },
        {
          "title": "A hunger for innovation must be matched with an appetite for risk",
          "link": "https://thehealthinnovationnetwork.co.uk/blogs/a-hunger-for-innovation-must-be-matched-with-an-appetite-for-risk/",
          "snippet": " To create an NHS hungry for innovation, we must increase our collective appetite for risk. Risk is not about patient safety.\n\nInnovation inherently carries a level of risk because if it didn’t, it most likely wouldn’t be innovative. Risk in this context never relates to patient safety, which remains of the utmost importance and assessed separately and addressed through robust regulatory processes and co-production.\n\nIn health innovation, the risk is in relation to the assessment of the impact of innovation. Simply put, the risk that it might not deliver on the time, cost or resource improvement intended, creates unintended consequences or simply doesn’t work out as planned. For example, making an administration element of a patient journey more efficient in one element of the pathway, causing bottlenecks elsewhere.\n\nThis inherent risk, if managed safely and appropriately, should not dissuade health and care teams from embracing innovation.",
          "date": "Jan 20, 2025",
          "attributes": {
            "Missing": "medical | Show results with:medical"
          },
          "position": 2
        },
        {
